          "text": "# Implementation Plan: Sort Feature for Query Command\n\n## Overview\n\nAdd sorting capability to the `query` command with `--sort-by` and `--order` flags. Support single and multiple field sorting with null values sorting to the end.\n\n## Requirements\n\n| Requirement | Decision |\n|-------------|----------|\n| Command integration | Add to existing `query` command |\n| Sort fields | Support single and multiple fields (comma-separated) |\n| Sort order |.asc/.desc flags,or `--order asc/desc` |\n| Null handling | Missing/null values sort to end regardless of order |\n| Value comparison | Leverage existing `Value::partial_cmp` impl |\n\n## CLI Interface\n\n```bash\n# Single field, ascending (default)\ncortx query 'status != \"done\"' --sort-by due\n\n# Single field, descending\ncortx query 'status != \"done\"' --sort-by due --order desc\n\n# Multiple fields (priority order)\ncortx query 'type = \"task\"' --sort-by priority,due --order asc\n\n# JSON output (existing)\ncortx query 'status = \"open\"' --sort-by due --format json\n```\n\n## Implementation Steps\n\n### Step 1: Update QueryArgs in `src/cli/query_cmd.rs`\n\nAdd sort-related arguments to `QueryArgs`:\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Args)]\npub struct QueryArgs {\n    pub expression: String,\n\n    #[arg(long, default_value = \"text\")]\n    pub format: String,\n\n    #[arg(long)]\n    pub sort_by: Option<String>,\n\n    #[arg(long, default_value = \"asc\", value_parser = [\"asc\", \"desc\"])]\n    pub order: String,\n}\n```\n\n### Step 2: Implement sort logic in`src/cli/query_cmd.rs`\n\nCreate a `sort_entities` function that:\n1. Parses comma-separated fields from `--sort-by`\n2. Applies the sort order (asc/desc)\n3. Handles null/missing values by sorting them to the end\n4. Uses`Value::partial_cmp` for comparisons\n\n### Step 3: Update the run() function\n\nAfter filtering entities, apply sorting before output:\n\n```rust\nlet mut matches: Vec<_> = all.iter().filter(|e| evaluate(&expr, e)).collect();\n\nif let Some(sort_by) = &args.sort_by {\n    sort_entities(&mut matches, sort_by, &args.order);\n}\n```\n\n### Step 4: Add tests in `tests/cli_integration_test.rs`\n\n- Test single field ascending sort\n- Test single field descending sort\n- Test multi-field sort\n- Test null handling (entities without the field)\n- Test sorting by date field\n- Test sorting by numeric field\n\n## Null Handling Strategy\n\nWhen a field is missing or null:\n- **Ascending sort**: Null values appear at the end\n- **Descending sort**: Null values appear at the end\n\nImplementation approach:\n```rust\nfn compare_values(a: Option<&Value>, b: Option<&Value>, order: &str) -> Ordering {\n    match (a, b) {Some(av), Some(bv) => {\n            // Both have values - compare them\n            let cmp = av.partial_cmp(bv).unwrap_or(Ordering::Equal);\n            if order == \"desc\"{ Ordering::Equal\n            } else {\n                cmp\n            }\n        }\n        (None, None) => Ordering::Equal,\n        (Some(_), None) => if order == \"desc\" { Ordering::Less } else { Ordering::Less },\n        (None, Some(_)) => if order == \"desc\" { Ordering::Greater } else { Ordering::Greater },\n    }\n}\n```\n\nActually, let me reconsider - for both asc and desc, nulls should go to the END:\n- Ascending: [1, 2, 3, null, null]\n- Descending: [3, 2, 1, null, null]\n\nSo nulls always compare as\"greater than\" any value, meaning they sort to the end regardless of order.\n\n## Files to Modify\n\n| File | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| `src/cli/query_cmd.rs` | Add args, implement `sort_entities`|\n| `tests/cli_integration_test.rs` | Add sort-related tests |\n\n## Testing Commands\n\n```bash\n# Create test entities\ncortx create task --title \"Task A\" --set due=2026-04-05 --set priority=1\ncortx create task --title \"Task B\" --set due=2026-04-03 --set priority=2\ncortx create task --title \"Task C\" --set priority=1  # no due date\n\n# Test sorting\ncortx query 'type = \"task\"' --sort-by due\ncortx query 'type = \"task\"' --sort-by priority,due --order desc\n```",
